\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {117}{\ignorespaces Four length-5 paths with \(M_5 \ge 2\) and \(X_5 = 1\) (top row), each paired with its reflected twin ending at \(X_5 = 3\) (bottom row). The first hit of \(m = 2\) is the gold star; before it, the original and reflected paths are identical. The reflection-after-\(\mittau \) is what swaps endpoints.}}{248}{figure.0.117}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {118}{\ignorespaces A length-6 path (blue) that touches \(m = 2\) at \(\mittau = 2\) and ends at \(X_6 = 0\), with its reflected twin (red) ending at \(X_6 = 4\). Purple arrows show how each post-\(\mittau \) vertex flips across \(y = 2\).}}{249}{figure.0.118}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {119}{\ignorespaces Empirical joint pmf \(\symbb P(M_6 \ge 2, X_6 = h)\) from enumeration over all \(64\) paths (blue bars) overlaid with the reflection-formula prediction (orange bars). They agree at every \(h\) --- that's the reflection principle.}}{250}{figure.0.119}\protected@file@percent }
